I used these brackets to secure an older (Frigidaire) dishwasher to my kitchen cabinets after installing granite countertops. The Frigidaire dishwasher was an older model and as such was not fitted or designed in any way to be used with side mounting. The dishwasher had brackets welded to the top of an aluminum band which held the plastic dishwasher body to the metal dishwasher door frame. But I couldn't use these brackets since you cannot screw into granite without possible damaging it.  However, even the aluminum band went around the dishwasher exterior.  There was absolutely no where to "hook" a bracket (you also could not screw into the aluminum band because you might puncture the plastic dishwasher body which would cause leaks and trash your dishwasher). So I purchased these brackets and J-B Weld 8265S Original Cold-Weld Steel Reinforced Epoxy - 2 oz. I mixed the epoxy and put a healthy amount on that aluminum band which I described above. I then stuck these brackets in that epoxy and used blue painter's tape to hold the brackets in place. I let the epoxy fully cure (15-24 hours) and then I tested. SOLID HOLD. Just like a a steel weld. I pushed the dishwasher back in the cabinet and used 1/2 inch wood screws to secure to base cabinet frame. The other side was next to a sheetrocked wall so I used 4 inch screws and found a stud close-by and screwed the bracket directly into a stud.  Mounting now is solid as a rock. Dishwasher does not move at all. Hope this helps. Good luck!

Recommendation for this product:
Pros:
1) cleans well.
2)Use smaller loads. And will clean two pairs of adult jeans on wash side, and spin dry one pair at a time on the spin dry side.
3) it is small to a point and light to carry or lift when empty.
4) Great for apartment use, and no bigger than six people per washer! If you have more than six people per week that you have to wash for I would recommend getting two of these.
5) works great if placed in the bathroom shower tub; make sure that you use proper electrical safety guidelines. Also maybe you should use a showerhead that is extended, or the inlet tube.
6) for a family of six; I spent 3 1/2 hours washing and spin drying six people‚Äòs clothes. About 15 to 20 minutes on wash, and 5 to 10 minutes depending on items placed in spin dryer for each load.

Cons:
1) The cord of this item is very short you will need an extension cord. Remember to use proper safety electrical guidelines if you place it anywhere near a tub or water source.
2) if the spin dryer is alone while working, it will shake the entire product. And could damage the machine if not properly secured.
3) The drain hose is very short, if you do not have your product elevated on a stand and secured above the drain area, the pump will only get 95% of the water out and leave some in the hose which can cause mold or mildew to fester if left undrained.
4) this may or may not be a con however, the inlet hose that it comes with does not secure very well to the Fossett or showerhead connection, so be aware of this.
5) The noise level is fine, however it would be nice if the machine came with a buzzer or a bell to tell you when it is finished. So you have to be listening for the machine to stop, or be watching it or set a timer for yourself. Or you will forget about it.

All in all, this product is extremely worth the money that I spent. I will recommend this product to everyone I know. After all, you‚Äôre already paying for water, so why not use it.

Like many, I bought this because I live in an apartment with no washer or dryer. Overall, I like it for what it is. However, potential buyers need to keep in mind that they aren't purchasing a fancy washer/dryer- this really can't take the place of a proper set up. For perspective, I use this to wash items that cant wait for me to get to the laundromat and baby clothes.

Here are some things to keep in mind with this item, and honestly others like it (as I don't think it's a brand/quality issue so much as a limitation of this product in general type scenario):

1. To drain the water after rinsing, the hose uses gravity. This means the drain needs at the base or below the washing machine to work. Don't attempt to pick this machine up while full of water. To deal with this, I put this machine in my bathtub while in use.

2. These aren't sturdy items. It is best to have it on the ground rather than on some sort of cart to drain into a sink, if you're thinking of trying that. They also become unbalanced quite easily.

3. The user cannot do a large load or put heavy items in the washer. I can probably fit 1 pair of denim pants in the rinse portion, but they will not fit in the spin cycle, at least not without the washer trying rocket itself off to space. Best to skip the spin cycle for heavier garments all together and just hang dry.

4. The spin cycle gets off balance easily. Make sure to evenly lay out clothes in the drum to get the best results. Also, you will need multiple spin cycles to get through all the clothes in the rinse cycle, as it is much smaller.

5. Be prepared to use a LOT of water. You will need to use multiple rinses to get all the soap out. This take some trial and error to get the right balance. Also, side note, much easier to fill the rinse basin using the shower head than the provided tube.

6. Lint! Invest in a lint roller. Or several. Once your clothes are dry they will need a good rub down with one of these.

Now for the tip...One thing I found that isn't mentioned is that the green funnel also makes for a handy tool to seal the foil lid. Just put the capsule in the black holder, the foil sits right on top and fits perfectly within the "outer" ring of the black holder, then press down with the green funnel and twist back and forth a bit while pushing down. UPDATE: I found that while this works, a quick press around the edge with the brush handle gets a much better seal - so my revised process is a quick press and turn of the green part keeps the foil in place and then a quick press with the brush handle to finish. Doing it this way, the process of filling a capsule only took about 30 seconds from grinding to popping it in the machine.

I bought my chemex after seeing it in a local coffee shop, and trying the delicious coffee it made. I thought it was such a cool yet simple coffee maker, and the final product was quite good. I bought the chemex and the special chemex filter, as the person at the coffee shop told me they were special filters specifically for the chemex maker (a bit more expensive than standard ones).

Anyways upong bringing my chemex coffee maker home, I was immediately hooked. I don't know what does it, but for some reason the coffee from my chemex changed the way I enjoyed my coffee, and makes an INCREDIBLE cup of coffee. Before I was using a single cup plastic melitta pour over and a french press...the chemex blew them both out of the water.

I think it's partially due to the full glass beaker design, which does not impart any impurities in the coffee that plastic potentially could. And I also think it's partially due to the filters, which is why I'm writing this review! The filters are extra think bonded filters, that seems to contain every single grain of sediment without sacrificing the delicious oils and aromas from the coffee beans. It allows for the perfect flow of coffee through the beans as well, slow enough so the coffee seeps long enough (like a french press, without the grinds in the cup).

I do recommend wetting the filter first before putting the grinds in. I think it washed out any filter flavor a bit (maybe placebo), and it also may help with the flow of the coffee. Also, not related to the quality of the filters at all, but I HIGHLY recommend you grind your whole coffee beans right before use...it makes a world of difference in the quality and freshness of your coffee. Ideally a burr grinder, but at least a spice grinder is better than nothing.

I've had many different driers over the years, and they've all dried clothes. The only differences were capacity, heat source, and features. It didn't matter the capacity, the heat source (gas or electric), or the features, they all had one thing in common, they dried your clothes. The permanent press cycles are nice, the cool down cycles are nice, infinite temperature settings are nice, but they are all worthless if it doesn't ultimately dry your clothes in a reasonable amount of time.

Then there's this drier. It is the absolute worst drier I have ever used. It will not dry a load of clothes on one dry cycle. Doesn't matter how many clothes are in the drier, how long the cycle is, the temperature of the cycle, items never come out dry. And I don't mean a little dampness or slight cool-to-the-touch around the waist line, I mean wet. It always takes at least 2 cycles, and often more, to get them dry. Especially towels. I will be up half the night restarting the drier every 75 minutes or so just to get one load dry! It must have 15 different drying cycle types, and it doesn't matter which one you use, everything is still is wet on completion.

This is the only computerized drier I've ever purchased, and it will be the last. Give me a good old mechanical dial for the amount of time and a 3-position switch for setting the temperature any day.

I bought this at Target last spring and while it wasn't the most perfect product, I was pretty excited about having it. When people complain about the taste, that's either them not rinsing out the machine initially (which I did) or just using water that isn't the best quality. I washed mine well a few times with hot soapy water and used water from my Brita water pitcher that I keep in the fridge. It suggests wasting the first few batches which I did. The ice tasted fine.

The ice is a very soft ice which is great for just eating alone. My kids loved it. They would just want a cup of ice. Pretty funny. But because the ice is very soft, it melts very quickly, especially in room temp drinks. But if you use a lot of it, you can get by with not being too bothered by that. It will make a batch about every 12 minutes which was nice.

As a side note, the ice melts while sitting in the unit, it is not cooled in any way. It's just like a cooler sitting in your kitchen. The warmer your house is, the faster it melts.

The machine is noisy while making ice (it's wasn't as bad as others state though, but then again I'm used to a noisy house with 3 kids. lol.), which I did not mind, but the machine also makes other noises that are not normal...but only after months of having it. There was enough water, but it sounded like the pump was on it's way out. I would unplug it for a few days then plug it back in and usually it was better. Not always though. My husband would tease, it's on it's way out! I knew it was close. Not even a year old.

A few months ago, it just stopped freezing the ice cubes. The machine goes through the motions of making ice, but doesn't actually freeze anything. What a bummer. So, a year old and now just a worthless piece of junk for $109.00 (luckily it was on sale at Target). I originally justified the $ by thinking I would use it at parties and for the ice chests on outings, but no you can't. It just melts too fast and there isn't enough for a party. I still ended up buying bags of ice for those occasions. Maybe if you bag up this ice then store it in the freezer???

It was an alright machine while it lasted. It did light up often that there was too much ice when there really wasn't or the right side where the metal sensor was had a few pieces barely touching it and then the left side of the basket was pretty empty. As others reviewers states though, just knock the ice down so it's evened out and then hold onto the metal sensor for about 20 seconds then it re-triggers it to start making ice again.

The machine is a descent size too. It was difficult to maneuver it around to clean it out. I won't miss dealing with that. I would clean it out every week. Something else I just remembered. After about 6 months of running it....all the stickly labels (the warning labels) got moldy (black) on the underside of the lid (cover). I thought how stupid to put something paper in an area with direct moisture contact. Gross. I scraped it all off with a razor blade and cleaned it really good. It would be better to take those off first or they should be covered with contact paper or something. What a dumb idea on Emerson's part.

So, if you are willing to spend the $ for ice for one year, then go for it, but if you expect a machine of that cost to last longer, then look for another one. I wish the "good" reviews stated how long they had owned it. Over the year, my machine was probably turned on and making ice about 80% of the time. I have noticed other machines that look identical to this with different names. I can't help but wonder if they are selling the same crappy machine with new names now. Just do your research.

This is perfect! This hose is very thick rubber. Bends great and again its thick. 1st thing, throw the hose clamp in the garbage. Do not use it. Its cheap and very thin. You wont get enough bite on the threads before it strips. I buy "pro line" hose clamps here on amazon for whatever size I need. They are decent quality. I didnt remove any panels for access. I tilted the washer back and shoved a step stool under it. There will be water in the old hose so have fun when you pull it off. All you need is decent scissors to cut the new hose. Make sure you cut the hose to the right size "diameter" of  the drain tube you are putting this hose on. I used the old mounting tabs that held the previous hose in place. You dont want the hose flopping around. Also, I only needed 6 foot. I didnt want the full 12ft hanging around with water in it. So the end that connects to the wall drain I cut it as well. Again scissors. Leave yourelf some extra hose so you can pull the washer out later. There is a piece this package gives you to attach to the end after cutting it. This is a VERY simple fix that takes 10-15min tops. When you're under the washer, look around for any other leaks or damage etc. Check your water supply hoses in back and see if there is any damage or sand/crud in them. They normally have screens in them. Now, get back to washing and hope thats all that was leaking!

I installed these 4 wheels on my Kenmore dryer. The dryer is a 1989 vintage dryer. Old in other words. These 4 wheels fit perfectly with no modification. They was no sloppy looseness on the shafts after installation. Most importantly they fixed the problem with noise.

The wheels are not red as the photo. Aside from that they look exactly like the ones I removed. The original ones have never been replaced until now. I bought this dryer new in 1989. I hope these last half that long. The clips worked and there were 2 for each wheel. The dryer has been in operation since these were installed and used 4 to 6 times a week. No noises.

I replaced the belt at the same time. I also removed the idler and lubed it. I have read concerns about lubing these wheels. I do not think using a layer of grease on the shafts will cause any problems. The dust that does get behind the drum will only stick to the external area near the wheels. I do not see how this can be a problem. Remember, the original had a layer of lube and they lasted until December 2014. I believe that's about 26 years. (the dryer was built in 1988)

If you need wheels and these fit your dryer, I would recommend a purchase. I have no connection with this or any company involved with this product. It is my opinion only. Thanks.

Perfect!  Used to replace Water Inlet Valve on Washer Model LAT8216AA.  The part number is 22001274 and has a 1/2‚Äù inlet.  This part worked even though the inlet nipple was smaller at 3/8‚Äù because this part came with a piece of tubing That goes over the nipple that made it bigger to fit the 1/2‚Äù hose on this washer.  The tubing can be cut away and removed easily so that the part can be used for washers with either 3/8‚Äù (Without tubing) or 1/2‚Äù (with tubing) inlet.  So, look at the picture and compare your original part to this one.  Measure the inlet nipple and rest assured that if it is 1/2‚Äù or 3/8‚Äù it will fit.  Also, on the original valve assembly, the electrical ends were on the ends but on this part, they are both on one side.  It didn‚Äôt matter at all. The Keurig smart brewer has a feature that recognizes QR codes on K-Cups and sets the brewing features automatically for the specific brand of coffee.  However, these pods don't have QR codes and the brewer doesn't recognize that a pod has been inserted.  I have addressed this by cutting the top off a used K-Cup that has a QR code and placing it on top of the pod, but it would be nice to add a QR code to the top of the pod so that the brewer will recognize that coffee has been inserted.  That allows the features to be set manually. Alternatively, there should be some way to bypass the automatic QR code feature and just brew coffee using manual settings.  The QR code feature is a subtle way for Keurig to discourage use of pods that are not sold by Keurig.

I raise my own chickens, meaning that I normally have a surplus of eggs. I got this device hoping that it would make storage easier. Turns out that it does just the opposite. I do not know if I am doing it wrong, but loading the eggs is easy, loading them oldest on top is hard to do. There are three spring-loaded trays with 10 holes each. I organize the trays so the tray with the oldest eggs is on top. After I use those eggs, I have to empty out the other trays and move every egg to the next level up, then do it again when THAT tray is empty. The only way to avoid this is to load 30 eggs and use them all, then load 30 again. It is so much easier to just use egg cartons., You can move the entire carton instead of the individual eggs.
One improvement that I would recommend is the ability to rearrange the trays. Of course, that would degrade the strength of the egg holder. Another would be to encapsulate the spring that flips the egg tray up. I have had to re-insert those springs several times, which resulted in me knocking stars off the review.

Sometimes, I have trouble trusting 5star reviews, but I had to leave one for this dishwasher. I. Love. It! I'm so happy with my purchase!

It's big, and doesn't slide under my cabinets, so it hangs over my countertop slightly. And that's my only con, so far. I've had this for a few months and I run in a few times per week. It's big enough inside to wash smaller pots and pans with a few extra things. It's fairly quiet. You do hear the water swooshing and you hear when the machine changes modes - i.e. from washing to draining. I can't tell you how loud this is in decibels, but I get hearing sensitivity sometimes, and this doesn't bother me. Especially if there's ANYTHING else making sounds at the same time - music, tv, etc. I specifically wanted something with a tank, so I didn't have to hook it up to the sink. That means, all I had to do was hook up the drainage tube (super easy), plug it in, fill it up and it was ready to go!

I use the short, 29 min cycle and it gets everything clean. Yes, I pre-wash any stuck on food, but I've done that for every dishwasher I've ever used.

There's an optional dry cycle for an hour after the cleaning cycle ends. I generally let it run for about 10-15 mins and then I pull the dishrack out and let it dry on the counter. Then, I either let the drying cycle run with no dishes inside to dry out the machine, or I turn it off and leave the tank lid off and the door slightly open for the same reason. Sometimes, this cycle bothers me, but not because it's loud, it's not. Just because it's a constant hum. It will continue humming after the hour until you press the power button or unplug the machine.

CONS: Doesn't fit under my cabinets, but none of the countertop dishwashers on Amazon would.
Sometimes the constant hum of the drying cycle bothers me. Because it's constant, not because it's too loud. But any music or tv or other distraction solves this issue immediately

I bought these hoping they would fit our Model #:JGP5030SLSS and for those that are seeking to use these to replace the cheap plastic knobs on the JGP5030SLSS be warned they do not fit. However if you‚Äôre handy and are willing to jump through some hoops they can be made to fit and I will explain how I managed to do it for anyone wanting to give it a go.

So the first thing to do is to remove the plastic insert in these replacement metal knobs and to do that I had to first pull out the metal D rings and then use progressively larger drill bits till the remaining material was easy to pull out.

Next I used a Dremel to cut the stems off of the original plastic knobs; the perfect length is actually a bit shorter than the fully available stem length.

The last step is a bit tricky and involves taking a small stub narrow pliers to push the sawed off stem piece into the new knob stem. It‚Äôs a very tight fit and is a bit counter intuitive in that the flat sides are 180 degrees opposite, which is fine, the fit will still be very tight and once in will require considerable force to push onto the gas valve stems and they will not easily come off after installing, so much so that I don‚Äôt think we will typically remove them but rather just clean them in place.

The final completed job is awesome and worth the effort but I‚Äôm pretty handy and so this is not for the typical person looking for an easy turn key solution. Unfortunately after exhaustively searching for metal knobs for our model and coming up empty, this was the only option. I colored the little dots in with some blue sharpie if your wondering, this was done just to add a little something extra, it‚Äôll probably wear off but for now they look like blue sapphires.

I left the ease of install unrated because my thinking is that if these were going on the intended product they would be much easier.

This is my personal use case. You may have a different situation, you may have exactly what I do. My purchase was spurred by a desire to have a washing machine in my apartment after being displaced from a home with a washer and dryer.

First off, it beats handwashing or scouring the town for a place to get quarters. I have the machine in my bathroom. I leave it outside the tub when storing, and in the tub when using. If you can lift a full clothes hamper to put in the car and run down to the laundromat, then you can lift this. This machine has done boxers and socks, a week of shirts, a couple bath towels and dish towels, and properly done one pair of jeans at a time. The best way to handle most loads is to do a wash load in the wash side, drain, do the same load with fabric softener, drain, spin half, spin the other half. The spin bucket will definitely jump if it's off-balance. Stop the spin, re-seat the clothes, try again. Once it finishes, hang clothes on hangers to dry. (I say one pair of jeans properly because I could not get the agitator to actually move two pairs around in the tub. Better to do one clean and take a little longer than to shove them in and have them come out dirty. No point in that, best to do it right.)

This is not a massive miracle washer, nor will it spin things completely dry in most cases, especially for jeans. I have intentions on getting a low power front-loading dryer or hanging fan dryer to complement it, especially for the jeans. But, my clothes get clean, and I can even watch the water as it drains to see exactly how clean. Little weird thing, I know, but it does something for me.

I could say there are more convenient products out here, but they will cost you more and are physically heavier. This does the job just fine and fits my needs and purposes perfectly. When it's laundry day, you do the work, but you don't have to run out to do it. Suits me fine.

This was ordered as a replacement for a switch that caused the 8-inch element to turn red-hot. The Magic Chef has been used for 30 years. I was not sure this switch would be a satisfactory replacement. It appeared to have the correct number of wiring contacts, and the current it could handle was the higher amount - 8.9 - 11 amperes.

The length of the shaft is about an eighth of an inch shorter than my original, and the entire switch was mounted sideways so OFF would be on top, just as it is on all the three other original switches. I used my laser temperature 'gun' to determine that the LO was the lower temperature and the HI was the higher temperature.

Other than those two points, the switch is a satisfactory replacement for the 30-plus year-old switch which controls the large eight-inch burner. The indicators on the replacement (Frigidaire) switch - L1, L2, H1, H2 and P - all coincide with the indicators on the original (Magic Chef).

If I remember in the future, I'll update on whether this switch lasted any length of time.

UPDATE: Middle of August 2017 and the switch is still functioning as it did when it was first installed. This switch rotates easier than the 30-year-old switches do.

At first I wondered if this was the right part, as the wash arm it was to replace was somewhat different in shape, although the dishwasher model numbers listed for this part matched that of our machine.

There are metal clips near each end of the wash arm's underside that, with the OEM wash arm, rubbed against the heating element in the bottom of the machine, preventing the arm from making complete revolutions as it sprayed. I suspect that this is what caused the previous wash arm to melt badly on the underside, as it was obvious upon inspection that high heat had been conducted to the plastic by the metal clips, virtually destroying the plastic underside of the wash arm near and around the clips. So, before installing the new wash arm, I applied some thumb pressure to the strips where they naturally curve a bit and enhanced the arc of those curved areas until they cleared the heating elements and allowed the wash arm to rotate freely through 360 degrees with no drag. That appears to have solved the wash arm issues. I also removed, cleaned, and reinstalled the screen and debris trap, which solved the issue of the machine's failure to properly clean a normal load of pre-rinsed dishes. All is well once again with our Frigidaire dishwasher. I would have given this part 5 stars were it not for the issue with the metal clips. Otherwise, it works fine.

My dryer is a Maytag Bravos #MEDB850 and Amazon specifically listed this kit as a match for my appliance. I'm only giving this product two stars because:

1. This kit is listed as OEM... it is NOT OEM. Do not spend the extra money just because you think it's OEM.
2. The drum belt does not have the same amount of inside grooves as the original belt (the belt has to line up with the grooves on the metal motor pulley).
3. The drum belt is narrower than the original belt.
4. The drum belt has a smaller circumference than the original. Granted, belts stretch out over time but the new belt was so tight it could barely barely fit around the metal motor pulley (on motor shaft) and the idler pulley causing a horrible noise from the motor itself. I'm sure it would have quickly ruined the motor.

I ended up putting the original belt back on (it was still in fairly good shape). So far the wheels seem fine. I'm not going to return the kit because the wheels are a pain in the arse to remove and replace plus I would still have a non-working dryer. Arghhh!

Dear Mr Riddle,

It it with disappointment that I am writing you about my experience with my LG french door refrigerator. I purchased this refrigerator from Home Depot on 12/7/15. It was installed in my new kitchen in April 2016. I liked refrigerator and all of its features so I was upset when it started intermittently making a loud vibrating sound in July. The sound was coming from the fan behind the filter. As the appliance is covered under the one year manufacturers warranty, I called LG customer service and was told to call a local appliance servicer called "Reliable Appliance Service" myself. The noise stopped by the next day and everything seemed to be working so I never called the service center.

Then, sometime during the week of August 22nd the noise started again. Within the week the fan stopped working. All the food on the top of the fridge was warm and everything on the bottom froze. Additionally the ice and water dispenser stopped working and the letters "E rF" were displayed. I called customer support hoping they could tell me what was wrong. They again told me again to call Reliable Appliance Service. I called Reliable Appliance Service and they said that LG needs to schedule the repair or it will be treated as a cash ticket. I called customer support again and was told that they need to submit a request to their service locator team. Several days passed and I heard nothing. By this time all of my food was spoiled.

On Friday September 2nd I once again called customer support and was told that they still haven't found a servicer. They would prioritize my case with the service locator team and would return my call on Tuesday, September 6. I never heard back so I called customer support again on Thursday September 8th. I was told that they were still trying to find a servicer that would be willing to come to my house 40 miles from Anchorage, Alaska, and that there was nothing more that they could do.

Needless to say by this time I am angry and exhausted. My refrigerator has been broken for over two weeks and your company has conveniently absolved themselves of any duty to fix the problem. Thankfully, Home Depot is willing to pick up the refrigerator and give me a refund. They will be here on Saturday September 10. I will then buy a GE refrigerator.

In the mean time I am telling everyone I know to avoid LG products as the appliances are very unreliable and customer service is unwilling to help. I am sure that you have an interest in keeping your company reputation in good standing with potential customers and therefore I am hoping that by informing you of my experience you can assist your team to make a better product and improve customer service.

At the very least your company should have been willing to pick up the appliance from my home and take it into servicer. Instead I was offered no help what-so-ever. I have spent hours on the phone with absolutely no interest on your company's behalf of helping. If there is one thing that I can hope come of this is that no one who I know buys an LG appliance. This has been literally the worst customer service experience of my life.

Before getting this, we were pan frying our steaks in non-stick cookware and it just isn't the same. They were always soggy, soggy, soggy. I didn't want to go with a cast iron skillet either because it still has the same problem as the non-sitck pan we were using -- the splatter! This broiler pan was just what we were looking for, since our oven didn't come with one. Now, at least the mess stays in the oven and cooking most steaks is super-quick: 6-10 minutes most of the time and depending on thickness.

Tip: I found it very difficult to clean off the baked-on fat and juices after broiling beef so close to the flame, especially when you don't have meat covering the whole surface and any juices that aren't covered by meat get really baked on. This happened to me when I had to broil 2 batches of steaks and the second batch was smaller. To make cleanup easier, place foil over the grill portion, press it down to form into the recesses as best you can, wrap the edges over the sides of the grill 1" or so, then use a butter knife to make slits in the foil where the grill slits are. This method makes it much easier to clean while still allowing the juices to drain and avoid soggy meat, which is the whole purpose of a grill pan like this. Note: I don't want to use pan cleaner sprays with heavy chemicals.

The coffee comes out very watered down and not strong at all. I think this is because the mesh is all around the cup instead of having a single small point for the water to exit from near the bottom. With regular K-Cups the water enters from the top and has to travel all the way to the bottom and exit where the needle pierces the cup. With this, the water can enter the top and exit almost immediately out of the side, meaning it touches less coffee before exiting the cup.

My Samsung front load washer stopped draining and the display showed a "Nd" (no drain) around the 20 min mark of a cycle. After a Google search and watching some videos I decided to open up the washer. To diagnose the problem, I drained the water and the load finished with a spin cycle. I ran an empty load and it did it again. After another drain I knew I needed to open up the washer. After lots of video watching and 20 screws I took off the washers outside panel with the door so I could look inside and check hoses. I took the hoses off that were connected to the drain pump. Once I saw they were clear I diagnosed the problem as a bad drain pump. I also noted I had the washer for 10 years and that is their life span. Thankfully the part has a part number on it so.
I just looked it up. And Amazon had it. 2 days later, it arrived. I already had old drain pump off so all I had to do was connect the new one to the hoses and power source and put the washer front panel back on. Took me much longer to diagnose and take apart the washer than it did to install the new part and reassemble the washer. Works great!

When arrived, I was concerned about if it is right part. Online description referred to a different number. Also sticker on the wire says - use only for some specific ignition system. After 20 minutes research found that this thing fits my requirements. Installation was easy. Disconnected power from the oven, cut wires from the old ignitor, replaced with the new one, stripped insulation for about an inch for each wire, connected using two provided nuts, verified the connection if it is tight, since it is an AC circuit there is no reason to care about polarity. First run attempted keeping one hand on the gas valve (just in case). The ignitor gets hot pretty quick and fired up gas furnace momentarily without any smell, pop sounds like it was with the old one. Switched off. Assembled oven. Run again and so far more the 20 times used the oven baking with different temperatures and no suspicious sounds and smells. This thing is doing it's job well. I'm satisfied. Four stars just for the confusing label and no any compatibility specification or list.

You can find my original review below, but after having owned this filter for a while, I would no longer rate it highly. Sure enough, the filter started out great - it worked as well as other, more expensive filters. A few weeks into using it, my fridge now shows the filter to be at 50% of its lifetime and my water has a terrible taste to it. Mind you, the taste that comes out of this filter is MUCH worse than the taste of the water that goes in!

In essence, my endeavor is, of course, to remove any and all traces of odor and odd taste from my municipal water supply. This filter, however, manages to make the condition of the water worse.

Thus, my verdict: Stay away from this filter!

Original Review:
There's not much to be said. You can either pay a premium and get a brand-name filter or you can save yourself a ton of money and buy this one. The outcome, as far as the taste of your water is concerned, is the same.

I will say that this filter seemed to trap quite a bit of air. After installing it, I had to flush the line until my water dispenser stopped sputtering - since I used a measuring cup, I know that I let about one quart go to waste before my fridge functioned normally again.

You should also be aware that this filter comes with a little tube of lubricant that you are supposed to spread on the little O-rings - something I had not encountered before. Doing so took a whopping five seconds and thus, is no problem whatsoever.

I love this (not so) little machine! Just realize that you need to babysit it. The ice basket is not a freezer. Every 7-10 minutes, it produces a handful of cubes. Multitask away; you will hear the cubes when they fall. Dump them in a container and put it in the freezer. Every time you hear a batch drop, take the container out of the freezer and add the new ice. Give a little shake. Return to the freezer. The first two or three batches of ice will be a bit wet and prone to sticking together (thus the shake), but after that, they come out colder and dryer.
I make a batch of ice that lasts me a week. The machine has a pretty big footprint so I drain it, dry it, and put it away when it's not in use.

I don't write reviews of a lot of products however I feel it is warranted for this product given the price. I bought this in June of 2022. The product makes excellent ice and is quick as described.

However, there are a few things I wish I knew before spending hundreds of dollars on this machine. We wanted an ice maker as we don't have one in our freezer/fridge as most people do, so we wanted ice available all the time. We decided on this countertop unit to have ice all the time.

It is very noisy. It started pretty reasonably but as it gets used more it increases quickly over time. Not a deal breaker because the constant ice was a fair tradeoff.

It does not keep ice frozen. It will melt and re-make the ice. Therefore, it is a constant cycle of ice-making. Again, not a huge deal because as the ice melts back into the water as ice is being made very frequently.

It is impossible to keep clean. See the photo attached. This is after about 10 days. This is because the water reservoir is internal and cannot be easily removed and cleaned as advertised.

I reached out to the company and they were responsive but stated the following:

"Please note that this unit is not to be kept running for 24 hours. The ice inside the tray when full will melt and keep making ice over and over. This unit is to be used to make ice and then the ice should be stored until the ice is ready to be used. "

This machine is the size of a small microwave. It is heavy. I don't want to spend a whole day making ice, moving it to our normal freezer then clean the machine, move it and store it and get it back out when I need more. Plus, I tried to store the small pellet ice for a later date and it all just freezes into a solid block of ice that can‚Äôt be used anyways.

Bottle line, if I could go back, I would avoid this product and spend my money on the GE Opal.

This product has a pretty serious design flaw. I have seen other people mention leaking problems. Sure enough, mine was leaking instantly once I started it up... dripping from the right edge about half way back.

I tracked down the issue, and you can fix this if you are just a little creative.

What is comes down to is this: If you look into the lower tank (take out the ice bucket) you will see the drain where water is recycled back to the top to be used again for making ice. That drain has a washer *with almost no pressure applied to it.* In fact it is just a friction fit. Pretty dumb. This could be easily remedied by having a threaded back side and a plastic nut so the washer would compress a little. With all the returns they are dealing with it would be a much more cost-effective solution....but I digress.

Anyway, what I did was to slice a synthetic wine cork in half (long ways). Squeeze the cork into the little indentation at the bottom of the reservoir. This puts pressure against the washer but still allows water to move. If you try this, it is at your own risk. Certainly *do not* use a regular wine cork because you will certainly get cork into your water lines. A synthetic cork, sliced cleanly, should be fine, but again... your risk.

For now... the leak is solved.

On another note, the blue "Ice Full" light was not turning off for me (which means the unit will not make any ice). I investigated the plastic lever that should turn that light (and the ice process) on and off. On the right side of the lever there is a cylindrical housing that probably holds a metal slug or a magnet... something that completes a connection so the circuit board knows the ice bucket is full. Well, my housing was empty. I wrote the company in order to get that part, whatever it is (seems a lot easier than sending the whole unit back). In the meantime I jumped those pins on the circuit board (which of course voids the warranty and should NOT be attempted by most folks, so don't mess around unless you understand what you are doing).

So, my ice maker is now working (though I can't leave it unattended or it will jam up with ice cubes... not a big deal for me) and it DOES make clear ice, which is the whole reason I got this unit for my home bar. It baffles me that they are so careless in the design and assembly. I'm sure they are spending far more processing returns than they would if they solved these little issues.

Just used the first time, made a really great cup of coffee. Since there are a lot of good reviews, I'll just mention some of my concerns going in:

Stability: there seem to be a lot of concerns and warning about the SlickDrip collapsing, as opposed to its rigid competitors. After using it, I really don't see any risk of that if you follow the instructions about how to add water. Also, following those instructions will give you a better tasting cup of coffee anyway.

Mess: is all the coffee going to end up in the cup? Will the last few drops attach to the surface and run off the edge? Answer: there is absolutely no residual coffee on the underside of the device. This tells me that every drop that went though the holes ended up in the cup. Although I haven't used them, I'm guessing the rigid plastic drip cups might not perform as well in that.

Clean up: with all the nooks and crannies, is this going to be a pain to clean up in non-kitchen environments? Answer: very easy to clean, but air drying is a little slower than a rigid device would be. Not a huge deal, but you may want to plan on drying with a towel.

This washer basin is huge - 4.7 holds everything and we have a family of 5. We almost bought the Kenmore Elite HE5T with steam but found out the regular units are 4.4 but the sale unit only available in "barolo red" was only 4.0 - big enough for most but size was our major factor in a new washer. So we gave up the steam and went with Electrolux. Electrolux does not make a steam washer, the steam dryer is in the wave touch model ($300 more apiece than the IQ touch). The main reason to me for steam is stain removal; not so much wrinkle removal, so IQ touch was fine. Apparently Electrolux and Bosch don't think steam in a washer is necessary; neither offer it. This washer/dryer is fantastic. I was concerned about the doors (as many are) but they are incredibly sturdy and you should have no trouble with them, I got used to the 'push' feature immediately. The tops of the units do scratch - we lined them with the rubber foam liners so we can use the surface area (you can get the wide at Lowe's in the tool section). Both are very quiet - washer spins so fast you won't believe it. I was also concerned about the extended wash time with front loaders but with the size of the bin I can almost double my loads. Also, Electrolux offers an 18 minute fast wash cycle. Dryer time is incredibly fast because clothes are almost dry when they come out of the washer - 20 minutes for drying in most cases.

UPDATE 6/3/11 - I checked back and saw the comments and Electrolux began offering a steam washer shortly after our purchase. Our Electrolux IQ Touch Washer and Dryer are still going strong and we love them. No issues whatsoever, and my teenagers do their own laundry all the time.

So this sounds crazy. But to install this and make it work you need a Phillips screw driver, and a knife or scissors, piece of tape.
1. Open the filter housing that has the filter in it. Take out the old one but DON'T chunk it just yet.
2. Take out the Phillips screw behind where the filter goes. The one closest to the front.
3. Disconnect the little wire harness and remove the little cover.
4. CAREFULLY squish each one of the white tabs and GENTLY pry the circuit board up.
5. Now look at the ge filter it has a sticker on it or towards the top 1/4 of the filter. If you look close you will see a square behind the sticker. You need this square. It's a small microchip. Pull off the sticker being gentle not to ruin it or bend it.
6. Cut the rfid or microchip out. And now looking at the circuitboard towards what would be back of the fridge tape with scotch tape the chip in the middle of the square on the circuit board. The rfid chip should be taped with the Shiney side towards the board.
7. Put it all back together just like ya found it.
8. Install this filter
9. Your fridge will say over 99 days blah blah blah. Ignore it.
10. Enjoy

This kit takes care of everything you will most likely need.  The directions are clear and easy to follow and there are lots of videos to watch as well. The metal filter works well, but I do get some fine grounds that come through even if I grind at a coarse setting. You can keep out the fine grounds by using a paper filter with the metal filter. If you are concerned with minimizing the amount of paper filters, you can re-use the paper filter multiple times when using with the metal filter, just rinse it off. The bearings fit good but the seal did not. After some bit of screwing with it I got it in to the point that I believed it would be ok. The issue I had was not the i.d. of the seal but the o.d. It was or at the very least appeared to be ever so slightly too large. As a result I would drive the seal, wait a minute, and it would pop back out. After a few try‚Äôs it finally stopped popping out and I was able to finish my repair. The washer was as quiet as new for a few weeks. Then the bearings started to make noise again, it is now nearly as loud as it was before the bearing replacement. My suspicion based upon what I found when pulling out the old bearings is that that seal popped out after being replaced and water has damage the bearings again already. I believe this because seal failure was what caused the problem with the OEM components.

This works fine on my LG washer model WM2101HW. The local parts place wanted $100 to replace both the broken plastic spline and the magnetic casing even though these clearly are separate parts and there was nothing wrong with the casing. The original part came with a plastic spline that wore out preventing the drum from rotating. This part is mostly plastic but has a metal spline built into it. In the end, this may just shift the failure point to a different location but overall, it looks much better designed. Ideally, it would be better if this were made completely of metal.

Installation is fairly simple but getting enough torque on the bolt that holds the part on can be tricky since the drum rotates as you tighten it down. It took two people with one holding the drum in place and the other tightening the bolt. I don't know an exact torque value but several years ago, the factory tightened drum loosened itself which likely did a great deal of the damage to the original spline. I made sure this was pretty tight.

My dryer run is 34'.  I bought 3 kits.  It was actually cheaper to buy 3 kits, than to buy extensions to reach 34'.  The length worked out just about perfect as the poles aren't always geometry straight when they're going thru the vent, so I needed every single extension rod (36' total) to clean a 34' duct.  As others have stated:  NEVER run the drill in reverse (counter clockwise), you will unscrew the connections and you will inaccessibly strand your rods and brush inside the vent.  I duct taped each extension connection point, but I don't think that's really necessary.  It will buy you a couple seconds of insurance in case you accidentally reverse the drill.  Probably smarter to just duct tape the fwd/rev button on your drill in the fwd position.  I put my drill on low speed which is plenty of rotation, in my opinion.  I tried it on fast speed and I seemed to have a harder time unscrewing the connections when finished.  I think fast speed way overtightens the connection points.  I cleaned from the vent exit point, going "upstream" a foot or two at a time, then reversing (not reversing the drill, that's always fwd/clockwise, but pulling out the brush to clear lint), while the dryer was running on 'no heat' setting.  That way the airflow pushes out what you loosen up, a little bit at a time.  If your vent is already plugged, this method probably isn't the best way to go.  All I can say is I got A LOT more lint out than I expected.  Two regular size Target bags, filled to the handles, full of lint and hair too.  That was one of the biggest surprises, how much hair came out.  Gross.  Can comfortably say that the dryer vent is completely clean now and done for half the price of a professional cleaning after a single use.  Plan on using it again every year.  If I had any critique it's the time it take to screw/unscrew each connection.  Not a big deal if you have a 10' run, but mine is a very long dryer vent run.  However, some kind of quick-connect would probably drive the price up too much.

This is our third induction cooktop (keep selling the houses after the kitchen gets remodeled).  We've had Bosch and LG previously with fantastic performance.  We liked that this one came with a pan that fits across the two bridge burners and the style of the controls.  The fact that there is a built-in timer that's easy to use is awesome.  But the performance just isn't there.  We were used to having powerboil settings that brought a cup of water to boiling in ~2 minutes, this one (regardless of the burner) takes significantly more time.  Additionally the induction elements don't disperse well around the pan as well as both previous manufacturers had, it seems the outline is much more of a guideline than anywhere close to the actual induction coil size (as evidenced by where water or oil boils on the bottom of the pans when in use).  Controls can be a little finicky too but it's nice to use a finger on the round part or the + / - buttons to tweak settings.  Also this thing requires a 50Amp circuit per the instructions, well we're not rewiring to 6 gauge wire from the existing 8 so I guess we'll see how it does on a 40A (keep in mind this in no way limits the power output of the burners just means we can't use all five at the same time).  Overall wish we had stuck with a Bosch or the LG studio series we previously had that featured much more powerful settings, more uniform heating, and still had the bridge burner functionality.

[[VIDEOID:mo3PN7CE2P74JSQ]]I recently traveled to Uganda (East African country) in October 2013. I had purchased this machine years ago for my own use and loved it. So I took it to a friend of mine who is a missionary in Africa for her to use. We both work as volunteers for a health care organization called Kissito.org. Kissito works with villagers in Africa to bring health and maternity care to villagers. So we demonstrated the washer to them after learning that the girls in African families must do all the family laundry each day before going to school. If they don't finish the laundry, they must miss school. Hoping to show the families something that could help them do their laundry well, and do it quickly, we took the machine into the villages. This video clip is one of a local villager who transports patients to the local health clinic demonstrating the machine to a group, including teasing a boy who is trying to turn the handle. This is the machine in action!

What I love about this machine is it is pretty sturdy, since it withstood a year of my daily use, plus it survived 500 African villagers cranking on it all in ONE day!

If you thought red Georgia clay was hard to get out of clothes, you haven't been to Uganda, east Africa. These villages have no electricity, no paved roads, lots of kids (average family has 7 children) and lots of dirty clothes. Families there LIVE in dirt huts, farm, play, work and have the dirtiest clothes imaginable, yet the WonderWash got load after load of clay and dirt soiled clothing CLEAN! The villagers were amazed, as was I.

I mean after all, my gym stains and smelly, lightly dirty clothes I expected to get clean, but the grime and dirt that rinsed out of the WonderWash when put to a REAL test was stunning. It was SO effective our organization is trying to find a way to get MORE machines to Africa. Why? Because the girls in each family are tasked with washing the family's clothes every morning before leaving for school. If they don't finish the laundry, they must MISS school to do so. WonderWash could CHANGE the world simply by providing the ability to wash clothes fast enough that these girls can do the laundry and get to school on time.

WHY WONDER WASH ROCKS
It's lightweight, yet sturdy. I mean, after all it stood up to the rigors of a hike and trip in the back of an SUV on really rocky, difficult roads to get to an African village! It traveled TO Africa in a plastic tub packed with medical supplies, and survived the airline's handling without a crack or scratch!

It is easy to assemble.

It's durable. More than 500 villagers each had a chance to crank on the handle over the period of ONE DAY as we moved into three separate villages and demonstrated the machine with clothes the villagers brought to us. Kids, men and women of all ages and strengths gave it their best and it kept on working!

It cleans! At one village we received a pair of pants a toddler had soiled himself in, a bloody towel from a health clinic, a pair of men's pants used by a man herding cattle and soiled with manure, and several very delicate, beautiful and colorful women's dresses, plus a large scarf. We washed them ALL in one load and they ALL came out CLEAN! Plus, they smelled GREAT!

I can't say enough GOOD about this machine. I used it in the USA for a year until I got a car and could go to the laundromat where there was also a dryer. The only thing NOT to like about this washing machine is you do have to wring the clothes out and hang them up to dry...not a big deal. It works and for the price there's nothing better! I love it!

I like it and it performs as advertised but be aware of what it really does. It is not like making ice in your freezer. The unit only cools when it is making ice. The cubes drop into an ice bucket and at that point it's not much different from a cooler. Gradually the ice melts and the water is returned to the reservoir. Eventually the machine will refill the ice bucket when the cubes at the bottom have melted down enough that there is room for more ice to go in at the top. Also, the ice that comes out of your freezer will probably be around 0 degrees Fahrenheit. The ice out of this ice maker is not as cold and won't have as much cooling as ice out of your freezer.

I bought this after knocking over the AeroPress a couple of time using the inverted method. The mess is just what you would imagine with grounds and coffee everywhere. I used the inverted methods because I like to stir longer to help maximize the extraction without most of the coffee dripping out as it does when putting the AeroPress in the upright position. This attachment gives me the best of both methods and I highly recommend it.

BTW, the permanent filter works well by itself with very little if any sediment ending up in the mug. However, I still use a filter paper with it because the paper absorbs most of the cafestrol, which is a saturated fat in coffee that gram for gram has been found to raise cholesterol level more than another type of saturated fat. With the amount of coffee that I drink my doctor recommended I stop using my beloved French press and move to filtered coffee (she also recommended I cut back on the amount of coffee I drink, but fat chance of that) as part of a set of other changes to my diet, namely switching to a whole food, plant based diet, to lower my cholesterol so that I could avoid having to take a statin. With such a major change in diet, it's hard to tell how much of a difference switching to filtered coffee made to the drop in my total cholesterol from 210-220 to 140 and LDL from 150 to 90. But it turns out I like the less bitter flavor with the paper filter.

One note of caution, when using a paper filter you still have to use the metal microfilter with the paper filter on top. I forgot once and with only the edges of the filter gripped between the cap and the cylinder and nothing under it to support it, as soon as I started to press the filter paper pulled out and ended up as a lump in the valve cap. Coffee would only come out when the paper wasn't covering the valve, but then the grounds came out as well. And when the lump of paper covered the valve nothing would come out.

Oh, and one last thing, despite what Fellows might imply, the pressure during the press is far too low to make anything like the crema one gets from a high pressure espresso machine. Instead what you get is a thin jet of coffee coming out of the center valve at a good velocity. This entrains some air as it goes into the coffee already in the mug. This causes some small amount of froth. But making the AeroPress into an espresso maker isn't why I bought this, so this little bit of exaggeration doesn't bother me.

This is my 2nd purchase of this product. The first purchase in Nov 2015, the second in Dec 2016. I will cut to the chase....these work well, do not leak and I have had no issues with them at all. So why the 3* review?

1. The ones purchased in 2015 had both NSF 42 & 53 certification on the box.
2. The ones purchased in 2016 ONLY had the NSF 42 certification.

This explains why there is conflicting information on this particular filter in the reviews. Sometime between 11/2015 and 12/2016 they changed the product, changed the box, or the product is the same but failed subsequent NSF 53 certification by an independent agency. Bottom line, if you value NSF 53 certification as I do, these will no longer meet your needs.

I purchased the SGF-LB60 for Kenmore refrigerator to replace the original part 469990, 5231JA2005A.

The SGF-LB60 is equivalent of 5231JA2005B, difference being the last letter B. The B series filter is suppose to filter more contaminants compared to the A, the description and the cartridge lists 13 different contaminants. Whereas the A only lists 2.

I used the http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B002C0A7ZY/ref=wms_ohs_product?ie=UTF8&psc=1#productDetails device to test the water quality.

Ideal drinking water should read between 0-50.

- Tested the water at faucet unfiltered, reading 193
- Original Kenmore 5231JA2005A, reading 147
- Tested the water from the fridge after replacing with LB60 filter, reading of 196 (slightly higher then unfiltered, surprise?)
- Tested a Poland Springs bottle water, reading 36

Mind you the original Kenmore filter was past due by over 3 months.

Now, granted I am not using state of the art scientific equipment, nor am I a chemical engineer. But the simple logic that my readings were better with the used 9 month old filter then they are with the new filter, which one would expect to produce better results.

Very disappointed.

Dishes are my nemesis. No, I really hate doing the dishes by hand. I had forgotten how life was without a dishwasher until I moved to NYC last year. Got a great old loft but no dishwasher. I wrestled for a year with a sink perpetually half full of dishes, until a friend suggested I get one of these counter top dishwashers. After doing some research, I ended up with this Koldfront one. Mostly because it was black, matched my kitchen, and didn't look all cheesy. It's changed my life. I've used it extensively for about 4 months now and have had zero issues. There's a dual tube that runs out the back and hooks up to your kitchen sink. You screw a little nozzle into your sink and the tubes just clip on when it's dishes time. I coil the tubes behind the unit when it's not in use, so it kind of just looks like a big microwave. Doesn't hold enough for a family, but for a single person or a couple it's great. Even disregarding the loading instructions, I stack it full however and run it and things turn out great.

Pretty quiet, no louder than a regular dishwasher. Takes about 45 minutes on the P3 rapid cycle -- only one I ever use. It's also more environmentally friendly than doing the dishes by hand, and is light on the power consumption.

Main weakness is the drying -- it's not as effective as a regular dishwasher, and will leave some sitting water on the bottom of coffee mugs, etc. Venting isn't great, I usually crack the door open after the drying cycle is done to help air everything out and let the moisture out.

Make sure you have the counter space, it's about 19" deep and 17" high. I love this thing. Great appliance if you don't have a regular dishwasher.

I ordered this fan for my GE French Door refrigerator after noticing that the area where the bottom of the refrigerator doors and the top of the freezer door make contact with the unit housing was becoming very hot to the touch. That symptom indicates a bad coil fan.
Even though it was supposed to be compatable it wasn't. However a fairly simple modification made it work anyway. The new fan looks like a basic computer case fan; square in shape with four mounting holes at the corners. Unfortunately with my existing fan housing the fan is incorporated into the fan shroud making it all one piece. I used an oscillating tool to cut away the old fan from the shroud leaving a nice flat surface on which to mount the new fan to the shroud. I used four 1 1/2" 8-32 machine bolts, four lock washers and four 8-32 wing nuts to mount the new fan and wing nuts to the OUTSIDE (the side away from the coil and toward the compressor) of the shroud. I sealed the fan using aluminum metal duct sealing tape. The two connection wiring harness fit perfectly. Be sure to give that coil a good cleaning after removing the shroud while you have access to it!
(TIP! be sure to unplug your old fan and connect your new fan before you remove anything but the rear access cover to your fridge. Verify that your old fan ISN'T WORKING before ordering a replacement and the new fan DOES work before going any further with the installation. Thankfully there are several handy YouTube videos that show how to do this job in great detail. With the units where the shroud and fan are one piece, like mine, the job more complicated because you have to remove a bracket that holds the end of the coil opposite the shroud end in place so that the coil can be re-positioned to allow for removal of the shroud but it's not that difficult to do.)
My fridge now works perfectly again!
Good luck with your project!

My Maytag Centennial clothes washer stopped working and was blinking the green sensing light. I was about to call a repair person however could not get ahold of them so i started looking into it and determined from the you tube video that it was the shift actuator, so I ordered one from Amazon it arrived the next day. It was very easy to install. I unplugged the washer cord pulled it out from the wall and tilted it over against the wall so I could access the bottom. Then removed the actuator by removing the plastic cover that had two hex head screws and two Phillips screws holding the actuator and a muti pin plug. Reversed that process to install new it only took about 30 minutes and after the computer in a few minutes recognized the new actuator in the machine it worked perfectly. I saved a whole lot of money doing this myself.

My experience was that it was very easy to install without anything but a flashlight and a Phillips screwdriver. Here‚Äôs what I did***: Turn off circuit breaker for oven, remove racks, remove two screws in element mounting plate, pull out element through the white insulation in the hole just a few inches until you see the two wires attached to the prongs on the old element, carefully slide off the wire connectors from prongs, remove element, slip on the same wire connectors to prongs on new element and double check they‚Äôre securely slid all the way down, slide wires and element ends back in the hole, replace screws through mounting plate attached to new element so it‚Äôs flush with the back of the oven, replace racks, turn power back on at the circuit breaker, and your done! Recommend running your oven at 400F for 20 minutes after installation with an exhaust fan on or a window open as there‚Äôs some burning smell that is normal for new heating elements when first fired up. Hope this helps anyone who was in the same situation as me.

***dont hesitate to call a qualified professional if necessary. This was only my experience and not meant to replace the manufacturer‚Äôs installation instructions. Always follow manufacturer‚Äôs instructions from your owners manual and wear proper personal safety gear***

The original 9 year old GE profile Microwave grille finally failed to close.  The plastic holding the return springs finally broke.  This replacement matched the exterior of the microwave perfectly.  Internally there were some differences.  The original grille had the two top mounting screws going into threaded plastic where the new one had metal u-clip nuts.  Improvement but with a problem.  Explained below.  The second difference is along the bottom of the new grille there where four plastic tabs that the original looked like should have been there but were snipped off.  These four tabs fit into four mounting slots on the Microwave.  The idea is you align the tabs with the MW slots slightly to the left and when fully inserted push the grille to the right locking the grille in place.  Seems a better grille fit solution but in doing the slide right part the screw nut u-clips became miss-aligned.  Now the screws only go in to non threaded holes.  I chose to leave it like this as the grille seemed attached solid and the opening and closing function worked perfectly.  I could have sheared off the four tabs and installed the new grille similar to the original but the tabs certainly made a difference in the overall fit of the unit.

In the past, a small refrigerator that I use for a wine cooler stopped working.  I did not discover the failure for several days until I happened to open the small refrigerator and discovered it was very warm inside.  If you have expensive wine stored in a wine cooler that stops working, it can be a costly failure beyond just the repair to the cooler - it can ruin expensive wine.  I purchased a YoLink X3 Temperature & Humidity Sensor and placed it inside the wine cooler.  The LoRa technology used by YoLink provides a reliable signal from the temperature sensor, even though the sensor is enclosed in a metal refrigerator, so my home automation system can now alert me if the wine cooler ever fails again, and I can remedy the problem before the wine is damaged by storage at high temperatures.

I am a mechanical design engineer/manufacturing engineer familiar with designing parts from metal and plastic injection molded products, like the gray base and the mating gray screw-on cover.

The problem with any machined or molded parts/assemblies is tolerances, especially with plastic injection-molded products. There is a "recipe" for such molded parts when filling the mold with hot flowing "liquid" plastic quickly....it's time and temperature dependant. Each run of manufacturing the My K Cup can be slightly different in dimensions by a few mere thousandths of an inch...creating a "gap" when the assembly is used. Possibly...

In the My K Cup design, there are multiple interfaces where loose or out-of-spec tolerances can cause a problem...ie, the thickness of the filter basket is dimension x.xxx", and there exists the gap between the gray base and the gray cover of x.xxx" when assembled. if all these dimensions and tolerances do not provide a leak-proof seal, there is a good chance the pressurized water will flow up to the cap and over the rim of the basket filter flange....and taking coffee grinds down into your cup.

I have tried all the solutions listed on so many good reviews (and used some of them below)....however, besides being a chore, I still got a different strength cup of coffee. Today, I finally realized what the solution to this problem is---it's missing a compliant gasket to eliminate any dimensional shortcomings between the dimensions of the flanged threads on the base and the cover, and the thickness of the flange on the filter basket, etc.

so I decided to take some aluminum foil from the roll and create a seal to accommodate for any possible tolerance issues. I pulled out about 4 inches of aluminum foil, and folded it in half. now I had a piece of foil measuring 2 inches by 12 inches long, but 2x thick. I then cut 2"x2" squares to cover just more than the diameter of the filter basket diameter. I also poked a hole in the center for those three fins found on the underside of the gray cover to allow for the hot water to enter the filter basket. Basically, I've replicated the foil found on original K-Cup design, but without the adhesive seal. Guess what? It worked!! Finally, no trimming of old K-Cups, no reusing old K-Cups...which may or may not be a health concern as others have mentioned.

so to make it hopefully more simple to follow, here's what I did, which includes hints and tips from many other commenters.

1) remove the rubber gasket/o-ring from the puncturing needle from the head of the unit, place a #10 stainless steel washer on the post, and carefully place the rubber gasket/o-ring back onto the post in the same orientation as it was before you removed it. This will keep the rubber gasket/o-ring from sliding back up the post.
2) grind coffee or coffee beans to a fine grind. 5-10 seconds in the small coffee bean grinder. too fine will allow fine coffee particles thru the screen...
3) place filter basket into gray base (i used a tall shot glass to hold the gray base during this process)
4) fill the filter basket 75% and lightly tamp down
5) prepare the 2 ply aluminum foil square so it's 2" x 2" square and place atop the filter basket
6) fold aluminum squares around the edge of the basket and gray base
7) while holding aluminum square in place, puncture center of foil with something to create about a 1/4" hole.
8) screw the gray cover onto the base. (Note, this can be tricky if the foil is on the threads between the gray base and gray cover...but it's not a steep learning curve...you'll get the hang of it.)

so having done this, i anxiously pressed start...and FINALLY, I got a good strong cup of coffee with freshly ground Starbucks French Roast! the only grinds in my mug was the too-finely ground coffee. I have to get that grind time down better...or learn to live with leaving 1/8" of basically cold coffee at the end of my cup of morning Joe...

It's hard to believe a $4000 oven had this issue. Ours was not heating up properly. If we put it one "Rapid Preheat" it would heat up and then lose temperature after the preheat cycle. I figured out what was going on - the convention coil at the rear of the assisting w/ the preheat and then once it reached temperature it would turn off and the regular "bake" coil at the bottom of the fridge would take over. However since our bottom coil was burnt out it would begin losing temperature after the convention coil shut off.

Anyway, installation is significantly different than most electric ovens where the baking coil is visible inside the oven. I had a bit of a difficult time figuring out HOW to remove this coil there isn't a lot of info on the web. I finally figure it out after looking at diagrams from one of the other "fix it" websites for a similar model. On our double oven the bake coil on the top oven went out. I had to pull the oven out of the wall to replace it by stack up some items (boxes of laminate flooring) so that I had something that was the same level to put it on. This oven is HEAVY, really heavy. I took a good amount of the oven apart trying to figure out how to get the coil pack out. Here is some advice for swapping out the coil on the top oven -

TURN OFF THE POWER TO THE OVEN(S) AT THE BREAKER PANEL
1) Pull the oven out of the wall about 4-6 inches.
2) Remove the latching mechanism in the top of the bottom oven
3) The metal plate between the two oven needs to be removed. There are screws on the side of the oven to do this. You may need to use a screwdriver to pop out the plate.
4) Look between the two ovens and you will see a push on cotter pin on the bottom of the top oven. Pull it out...
5) After the pin is out there is a panel/door that will drop down and allow you to pull out the box containing the heat element/coil.

After researching that a GE OEM replacement timer knob for my GE Dryer was over thirty-dollars, I found what was was to be compatible with the GE Part number. These knobs offered a no-questions asked, lifetime warranty and so I purchased them. Once received, they looked exactly like the GE OEM Time knob, but when I swapped it out with the old knob, I saw that knob was not a snug fit to the shaft of the timer. Turning the replacement knob between the control settings, you could see and feel the play, which eventually will cause failure of the knob.

Knowing that these replacement knobs aren't a snug fit, like the OEM knobs, I took the GE version apart and found that there's a fitted metal sleeve that' inside the GE knob, which gives years of longevity to the factory parts. In an effort to make these new knobs work similar to the GE knobs, but this metal insert won't fit.

Due to what I found out, comparing the GE and these replacement knobs, I cannot recommend them or can I recommend paying $32.10 to an online appliance parts seller. I'd recommend using one to these online sellers search out the exact part, compare sellers and but the actual appliance manufacturer's part and forget the cheap replacements like I've done. As in many cases, that nothing beats the factory original.

Since I‚Äôm anal about researching items before I buy them, I researched the AcuRite and sensors before purchasing. I wanted to monitor the indoor temperature in the house while I am out. After reviewing customer responses, I put batteries in the sensors before starting any configuration. The setup went well and I think having the sensors enabled helped. I agree with customers that instructions are vague. I was waiting for downloads/updates on the unit but could tell if they were done according to AcuRites instructions. After waiting 2 hours I assumed updates were done (lights blinking/solid on their instructions were no help determining if finished).

The Hub found all the sensors however as another customer commented, you don‚Äôt know which one to use. I wanted one in the basement, one in the main house and one outside. Took me a few hours to figure out which temperature was related to that sensor. I did have to do a reset a few times for the sensors to show the actual reading. Since a few were off, I tried to adjust (calibrate) on the web site. It never took. I deleted those and added them again (removed batteries before) with the calibration I wanted. They then displayed correctly.
All is working now and thru a few adjustments mentioned above it is working. I also previously had an AcuRite 5 in 1 outdoor unit and it found that as well. So now I can see all the house including the outdoor 5 in 1 unit.

Considering all the other options out on the market, this seems to be working for me. I hope not to experience failure in the system in a few months like others have reported. Thus far the unit is working as I wanted and I can view this from the downloaded app on my phone and tablet.

OK, it's a no-brainer decision to get this unit.  When our 11-year-old Kenmore (model #:106.56826600) ice maker died I decided a DIY approach made the most sense given the cost of a service call vs a straight out replacement.  Like other reviewers I first went to Google/YouTube and got smart on how the system works.  I developed a "Probable Cause" checklist and initially considered a frozen water line the culprit.  First, I removed the old ice maker to access the water line....Steps: Remove the ice maker door, tape shut the left hand ice level sensor door, and push in the two catches under the ice maker...it will slide right out (don't forget to disconnect the wires).  Wow, the water tube coming from the top of the fridge was frozen solid so I used a small funnel and hairdryer set on low to melt the blockage.  I reinstalled the unit only to find it still didn't work so I moved to step two and used the "jumper wire" procedure to manually advance the timer wheel...it failed both tests. I then realized the frozen water line wasn't  the problem, but was due to water backing up since the old unit had totally failed.  There was an additional  YouTube video that discussed replacing the ice maker's small motor and doing some soldering that I decided was not worth my time so I ordered the Supco unit.  It arrived as expected, the instructions are excellent and written for a DIYer vs appliance tech. Another reviewer called the unit "cheaply made"...I disagree, I thought it's construction was more than adequate for the task, after all it's an ice maker not a Pace Maker.  The unit went in easier than taking out the old one.  Don't forget to position the water line inside the small fill cup...long-handled needle nose pliers work well here.  Be sure to save all the old unit pieces and hardware as you'll need them in the new unit.  As a final step and maybe unneeded I cycled the power to the entire fridge, via circuit breaker with the ice maker switched off.  My thought was to clear any remaining fault codes, much like rebooting a computer after installing updates.  The ice maker dumped out it's first load of cubes a little over two hours later.  I discarded the first three batches and installed a new fridge filter (it was nearly due anyway).  Over night the ice tray filled and the ice level optical system worked perfectly shutting off the ice maker when the hopper filled. Finally, the Supco ice maker produces more and better quality cubes than the old one ever did.  So, for $45 and an hour of your time this is a no-brainer fix.

I just know that the mechanical engineers at Maytag are sitting in a bar, in downtown Benton Harbor, Michigan; just laughing away at the poor fool who is going to be fixing their own dryer. This comes from my 37+ years experience as an electro-mechanical service repairman.

Access to the over temperature fuse and the high temperature switch are not the easiest to get to. Use some surgical hemostats and a magnetic 1/4 inch nut driver to get the job done. Having nimble fingers helps too. Put the wires onto the fuse before you install the part under its mounting tab. You don't really want to drop the fuse nor any screws into the inner depths of the dryer.

Replace both the fuse and the upper temperature limit switch, as the limit switch is most likely shorted closed - you may also have a dust clog that is causing the dryer to overheat and eat fuses.

Needed a washer for our apartment that was portable, ran on 110V, and didn't need extensive hookups.
