When the package arrived there was no damage and everything looked good, packaging was nice and it was great having to just lift the box up instead of trying to dig this thing out of Styrofoam. So far my biggest complaint is that the tub itself has severe cracking and pieces missing, there was no rattling in the tub nor did I see any loose debris, so its possible this tub was damaged during production and was assembled with it; It seems to not affect the functionality but I worry over time it might split down or have serious issues when doing a spin cycle.

Speaking of functions, as a washer this thing works great. We washed a microfiber throw and some towels for the test run and they all came out smelling clean and dried off really well, only thing so far is that the ball lock valve for the sink adapter leaks a little bit when its on standby, but not by much.

Overall this is a great washer if your apartment doesn't have hookups and their facility costs $4+ a load for some small standard washer, however I'm going to knock it some points because it left the factory damaged; With all the neat packaging you would have thought someone at QA caught the damaged tub, I'll revise after getting in contact with Panda and seeing how that goes.

The most serious is the use of a nylon axle and spindle for the impeller drive shaft and food-grinding chamber -- it's easily stripped at the splines or sheared at the edge of the grind chamber.  They should have used a metal axle and spindle -- but come to that, they should have sold it separately so you aren't obliged to pay the price of a new motor to get a thirty cent part. Steps to replace:
1. Remove 5 screws attaching hinge to dryer (with someone holding the door so it doesn‚Äôt fall).
2. Lift up door and hinge assembly vertical until two hinge clips release free.
3. Place door outside face down and unscrew 6 screws around circumference of inside door. Lift inside door away from outside.
4. Unscrew first set of 2 screws securing hinge.
5. Unscrew second set of 2 screws securing hinge.
6. Remove hinge assembly by pulling hinge opposite inside door.
Reverse order to reinstall. Keep track of which screws go where there are three types. Also hand tighten the 6 interior door screws given they seat into plastic. They strip easily if not careful.

The original, factory belt had deep 'ribs', that are made to engage the grooves in the drive pulley. This belt didn't have these deep ribs, rather very shallow notches. The belt was also about 1/2 to 3/4" too short. You can get it on, but it is a bear, and will "max out" you idler pulley.

Here is a tip to help you put it on. You're basically working though a hole in the back that allows one arm access. So with one hand, cocking back the idler pulley AND trying to force a belt on that is too small.
There is a tiny hole on the idler pulley arm that aligns with another hole on the bracket when the arm when it is at full tension. So you can stick something (like a screw) in that hole to "hold" the arm back allowing you to work with the arm cocked. This leaves you with the only the task of stretching on the belt. Then you can remove the piece from the hole, and the tension pulley will put back the pressure on the belt.

The pump lasted 5 months before the shaft broke and the impeller fell off.
During those 5 months, it made a loud electrical buzzing sound while pumping (as one other reviewer noted).

Since I'm only the second reviewer to note buzzing, I assumed I had a dud. I attempted to claim the "lifetime warranty". However, when I followed the email provided, I received this immediate response: "You are receiving this email because you have inquired about an Amazon order. Please note that this email is for a brick-and-mortar building supply company located in the state of Maryland, and NOT for the unaffiliated online appliance company you purchased from. They have fraudulently used our contact information for customer service. Please refer back to Amazon for customer service regarding your order. Thank you."

I concluded:
- The email is true. This is legitimately a fraud and not sold or manufactured by BlueStars.
or
- The email is lying and they don't want folks redeeming their warranty.
But what's for certain is, THERE'S NO WAY TO CLAIM THE LIFETIME WARRANTY.

Also, make sure you position it so that the opening to the reusable cup is towards the top of the Keurig and not the bottom. We are very happy with this range. Goedeckers did a great job with the delivery including choosing an endpoint delivery outfit that was very helpful and patient (we live in a rural area and we can be difficult to find--because it is gas they could not install it but they helped unpackage it and with the inspection, and took all the trash from the packaging with them). I converted it from NG to Propane and found it to be straight forward. I did have to purchase a new valve for connection to my gas line (not the fault of the range) and the recommended, new, flex tubing et. al. but that was to be expected. The only caveat I have is that the location of the oven orifices is somewhat unclear as is the necessity of removing the burner tubes to reach them but once you understand where they must be, the rest of the installation is logical. We have now been using this range for about a month and everything we've done with it has been great. The flat racks for the top surface are very handy and because they are not slick, keep pans in place stirring, the burners work as advertised and provide an excellent range of heating to choose from, and the grill burner (and grill) work as expected. My only caveat to use is that the burners do not seem to have infinite variability between high and low but tend to jump a several points throughout the dial rotation--the jumps are small and there are more than a half dozen so this has not been an issue.

Update: We decided to reduce this from five stars to four because right around the two year mark one of the gas valves failed and had to be replaced at a cost of ~$45. If I did not have the know-how to do this, it could've run into a couple of hundred or more depending on things like location, availability of discount for the valve, etc. I've never heard of a valve failing. For those who are interested, it simply wouldn't turn any more--after replacing it I took it apart and it was not a fault in the safety feature that requires you to push it in first before you turn it to on/light, after removing that part of the valve, the actual valve still would not turn.

For the reviewer who suggested that "date code 200709" was 2007... No. The format is YYMMDD, so the product that you reviewed in October of 2020 was manufactured July 9th of 2020, just four months prior to your purchase.

As for reviewer Lily who said, "inside it's new, outside it's old" with photos... remove the protective plastic film wrap, dear! The whole purpose of that film wrap is to prevent scratches during transit. Once your peel away all the wrap from the top and sides, the exterior will look polished and clean.

We own an older version of this burner and it does a good job of providing a reliable source of heat for your pots and pans, but the knobs are poorly made.  After eight years of use, all four of the knobs have cracks in the bottom cylinders which fit over the metal controls in the main part of the heating unit; the knobs began failing two years ago.  If you do a search for replacement Bosch knobs you will find that other folks have had similar problems.  We filed a complaint with Bosch and their management team reviewed the photos that we sent and determined that because it had been eight years since we purchased the stove top that they would not be willing to provide replacement knobs. They best that they could do would be to offer us a 20% discount on the cost of the knobs which the sell for approximately $25 each. Given that the total cost of replacement would still be about $100 for four knobs, we declined their "generous" offer. I find it ridiculous that a major appliance corporation seems to feel that their knobs should not last more than six to eight years from regular use in normal conditions.  We take good care of our appliances and vehicles. I have a Kenmore washer/dryer set that last almost 20 years without any major repairs being needed. Sears makes some great knobs!  And I owned my last automobile for 13 years without it needing major repairs; Honda Pilot's are awesome.  So, if you don't mind taking the risk that the knobs on your appliance will fail after six to eight years of use, then this is the stove top for you. Otherwise, I would consider another brand.

For me, the downsides are; It requires a lot of user attention to get through a load or several loads. The spinner holds about half of what the washer holds, so after your first wash, you move half to the spinner and let it spin, then find a place to put those clothes while you load and spin the second half. then put them all back in the washer for the rinse, followed by a second series of the same thing...for each small load. That being said, I knew all that when ordering, and so it's more that I am disappointed after experiencing what it's actually like to wash with this, but they were clear about what I was getting. It would have been MUCH better to have the spinner of the same capacity as the washer. And even better if they were both the same thing, but they have those, and I didn't buy one because this was cheaper and more portable.

Other notes are that when you start the spin, you have to hold the unit steady while it spins up to full speed. Once it's at full speed it's fine, but getting there involves a lot of vibration and it moves all around. Mine also occasionally makes a grindy/clicky noise for a few seconds during the wash. I hope this is normal operation, and not an indication of something about to break. If it does break, I'll update this. I'm not sure what the supply hose is supposed to fit on. Not any faucet or hose valve I have in my house or have ever seen for sure. Maybe something that is standard in Asia?? But I just fill it with a garden hose and that works fine, and is probably faster too. Finally, it's not exactly a water saving type of washer.

BUT, like I mentioned at the start, I got exactly what was promised, and it should work fine for my needs. But it's not something I would buy for long term use.

I bought this to replace a 36" GE Profile Radiant cooktop. I wanted gas; my wife wanted this. We got this.

Installation was easy, as the previous cooktop had the same dimensions and wiring. That was a bonus for me.

I wanted to find things about this induction cooktop that I didn't like. For example, my wife read that it boiled a cup of water faster than a microwave. I was skeptical.

So, eager to disprove this bit of puffery, I measured out one cup of water and poured it into a vegetable steamer pot. Ready with my stopwatch, I pressed the on button for the "burner." I pressed High on the smallest cooking element on the cooktop and Start on the stopwatch simultaneously. Precisely 35.21 seconds later, the water was at a rolling boil! It made a believer out of me.

We have experimented with settings for cooking different foods. Without going into too much detail, 4 or 5 covered most things. Even boiling water for pasta does not require the High setting after reaching a boil, unless you want it bubbling over!

The downside is your cookware. I'm a huge cast iron fan. That's good, because they are perfect for induction. We find that our cook settings are always one level lower with cast iron than it is for any other ferrous cookware. Plus, even heavy cast iron heats up quickly on induction. We use silicone pads to keep the cast iron from scratching the glass. Works great!

My wife likes her pots and pans light. Aluminum doesn't work with induction. No surprises for us there. What was surprising is how many stainless steel pots aren't true steel. We ran a magnet test. All save one of her lightweight stainless steel pots and pans failed. So did her aluminum with copper and steel cladding. Just not enough ferrous content for the magnet to stick... or the induction unit to sense a steel pot/pan. Guess who's wife just got new cookware?

Cleaning is not hard. As the cooktop doesn't heat up, nothing cooks on. Just wipe the glass clean! The cooktop comes with a small sample of Weiman Glass Cooktop Cleaner and Polish. Take GE's advice: buy it. Nothing you've got under your sink will work as well. Everything else leaves streaks. Everything. Even water.

Safety is what drove my wife to want this cooktop. The cooktop is not hot moments after we remove the pot or pan. If you, like me, counted on the pan remaining hot after turning off the gas or power to your burner or element, you'll need to use the warming element instead when you cook on this cooktop. The pan cools off rapidly once the power to that element is off, as the induction element radiates no heat.

The only complaint that I could make is that the light gray markings inside the glass are too light to see easily if the glass is streaked.

They never hold our plates upright, limiting the number of dishes we can load. The upper (3rd) rack just didn't work for us... we took it out after the first week, as it only prevented us from placing tall glasses in the top rack. If you lower the top (2nd) rack to wash taller glasses, there's not enough space in the lower rack for our plates. The baskets for the silverware are small and are lidded with flip-up covers with slots for the silverware. Most of our silverware drops through the holes in the tops of the lids, which is fine. But if you have to open one of the covers to wash larger items, use caution as the covers strike the side of the dishwasher block the rack from closing properly. You can break the cover, or the rack will twist sideways when you attempt to slide it into the unit.

Many have complained that the latch on the door doesn't work properly... in fact, the problem is that the top rack does not go all of the way in unless you're very careful and push only from the center of the rack. If it doesn't snap in place, the door won't close completely, and the dishwasher will sound an error. Likewise, if any item in the lower rack hits the door, you're likely to have a problem. After finally working through this issue, we've not had any problems with incomplete cycles.

This is an update the review I left yesterday, upgrading the MaxBrew from 3 to 5 stars. First of all, let me say that this company has OUTSTANDING customer service. I contacted them regarding the fit problems and a live person called my cell phone within an hour. The rep explained that Di Oro had to remove one of the notches (there used to be two) to make the filter work in the new Keurigs. The notch is there to protect the filter and the piercing pin, so the piercing pin has to fit in the notch (you can see the piercing pin in the K575 in the first picture below; it's at the bottom). The notch in the MaxBrew (at the bottom in the second picture) has to fit exactly over the piercing pin, or the top of the filter juts up and you have to use force to get the brewer to close. It takes a bit of experimentation to get it just right, but if you put the MaxBrew hinge on the left and adjust it until you have it precisely over the piercing pin (third picture), it works great! The customer service rep was very friendly, very clear and gave me advice on the carafe version of this filter, which I plan to order today. All in all, a very positive experience.

I'm pretty mechanically inclined and with the help of the internet I determined this fuse was the cause of my dryer no longer functioning. After unplugging the dryer I removed the original part and "hot wired" the connectors together, plugged the dryer in, and it started right up. Local appliance repair stores in my area charge about $20 for the part and about $150 to replace it.

Taking the back off the dryer was the most time consuming part of the installation. Replacing the fuse itself took less than one minute, two electrical connectors and a small screw. The new part was identical to the original and functions as it should. It fit my Kitchenaid Super Capacity Plus dryer. Prior to the fuse burning out I was having to dry my clothes for one and a half cycles to get them completely dry but after replacing the fuse my clothes are dry the first time, every time.

A $6 part and about 20 minutes saved me from a $200 service call or having to replace my dryer. The seller even reached out via email to make sure that my issue was resolved. I received better customer service on such a cheap item than I have on much more expensive items in the past. I would definitely buy again and would recommend this product to anyone.

We got a nice bag of ground coffee and wanted to use it, but we've been a K-cup kitchen for so long that I needed to find a K-cup solution. I tried this product - Breworo, and also the Delibru Reusable K-Cups, and the Keurig 119203 My K-Cup Reusable Coffee Filter. These Breworo k-cups were the winners. I appreciate that there's a scoop included.
(Picture shows the Keurig 119203 on the left, Delibru in the middle, and Breworo - this item on the right)

Brerworo K-cups (this item) - best
Pros: Water is forced into and not just on top of the grounds. The bottom is solid, not mesh + the designs on the sides keep the coffee in a bit longer to develop the flavor. The bottom has indentations to avoid contact with the sharp metal that pokes the hole in plastic K-cups.
Cons: Slightly longer brewing time (additional 10 seconds maybe? - the more you pack down the grounds, the longer it takes & more flavor)

Delibru Reusable K-Cups - mediocre
Pros: Raised bottom to avoid contact with the sharp metal piece in the insert. Quick brewing time is the same as a regular K-cup.
Cons: While the water is dispersed on the top like a rain head shower, the fact that it's mesh all around meant the water ran out somewhat quickly & the coffee didn't develop full flavor.

Keurig 119203 My K-Cup Reusable Coffee Filter - would not recommend
Pros: Unlike the flip open tops on the Breworo & Delibru, this top screws on so it won't break off. You need only one of these instead of 4 (backups?).
Cons: You have to remove the existing insert in the brewer and replace it with the one included on the filter... for 2 reasons, first is so there's no sharp metal point but also because you *must screw the top on* in order to safely brew! The first time I placed the filer basket into the insert & set the top on... huge mess of coffee grounds & water everywhere. There is nothing that forces the water in like the Breworo so it just goes on top of the grounds. This is open mesh on the sides like the Delibru but without the rain head shower to help soak the grounds, so even having a solid bottom doesn't help. After multiple attempts, this best this filter produced was a quick cup of tan water.

My son turned me on to making a single serving of coffee with an Aeropress several years ago. While not as simple as plugging in a Keurig and pressing a button, the coffee that results is 10X better than the thin stuff than comes out of a K-machine.

Wait, make that 25X.

Aeropress is designed to use a small paper filter that is disposed after each use. They're not expensive, but can be a bit hard to find in the local stores. Amazon sells some reusable metal filters and they work well too. But along comes the Trobing Airflow Valve Filter system that combines a metal filter with a unique base that has a tiny opening for the brewed coffee to pour into your waiting cup.

That tiny opening is the difference between normal Aeropress coffee and this brew. It acts somewhat like an espresso machine in which coffee is forced under pressure through the grounds. And, somewhat like an espresso machine, you get some foam - almost crema - on the top of your coffee cup.

So does it work well?

Well, you're not going to think you just ordered an espresso at a coffee shop that uses an $8,000 La Marzocco espresso machine. But you will find a very nicely brewed cup of coffee that somehow tastes stronger than a cup brewed with stock Aeropress parts. The foam bubbles that the Trobing Airflow produces are larger than the tiny bubbles that make up true espresso crema, and they don't last as long either. But this device is really cool and makes great coffee.

A few watch-outs:

- first, read the directions! Trobing suggests pre-warming the Aeropress and your coffee cup with almost-boiling water. Do this! Then drain the Aeropress and add the coffee, then more almost-boiling water. And wait. Wait a bit more. It's worth it, even in a Keurig world. Then press that Aeropress plunger down and smell the difference between real coffee and fake machine coffee.

- second, the key to the Trobing is the tiny rubber valve in the center of the base. It comes out, and if you're not careful, it could disappear when you clean out the Aeropress after brewing. Trobing thoughfully includes a backup valve in the box, but lose both and you're back to using your stock Aeropress parts.

- last, the metal filter that Trobing uses only correctly fits into the base one way. If you can't easily lock the base of Trobing on the brew chamber of your Aeropress, then you have the filter in upside down. Flip it around and you'll know what I mean.

[[VIDEOID:b9fe1fa10bea552981792fd9d105a504]] I love this portable ice maker. I take it on trips in my pop up camper. I use it to supplement ice for parties. I make more ice ahead for my cooler on long trips or short ones to the park/beach. It's even fun to watch the little waterfall that makes the ice. It has all the features you would want.

Pros:
small footprint
does not need water hookup
automatic cut off when full
makes ice quickly - about 15 minutes/cycle
ice falls into tray in layers which maximizes what it will hold
low power consumption

Cons:
a little loud for camping, but just turn it off when not making ice (you can hear it in the video)

Now this is a next level item for preppers. Who else will be making ice when the power is off? One nice thing about making ice is it can be moved to your cooler to help preserve your perishables. The low power consumption is a plus, so it does lend itself to a prepping/off grid scenario. I hate to do this, but I am giving it just a 4 out of 5 because it should be on your C or D list as far as priorities. Get your food, water shelter and security in place then consider a 'luxury' like this.

Let me start with the pros. This oven is really nice to look at. That's where the good ends. Don't be fooled by the "commercial-esque" aesthetics. I bought a home with all brand new Thor appliances, and they have all been AWFUL (but back to the oven).

During COVID, we've been cooking a lot more than usual. The oven started tripping my electrical breaker any time we went to use it. Burners were fine, broiler was fine. I had an electrician come out to check the breaker and my house wiring was fine. Must be the oven.

I find out that the igniters in these ovens can go every 6 months to a year; so I bought an official Thor replacement through a local distributor. Because of COVID, I wanted to do the repair myself (the less people in my house the better).

I opened up the stove today to do the repair, and what I found blew my mind. The gas burner inside the stove melted over time because the glow bar got too hot, and actually started FLOWING UPWARD INTO THE IGNITER!!! The reason my breaker was popping was because the gas burner was shorting against the glow bar! What a safety hazard. I could have burned my house down because of this.

How does a product with this type of failure even make it to market?! Aside from this; we've had issues with the front right burner not igniting properly, and the knobs on this thing get HOT. Like, insanely hot.

Just do yourself a favor and spend the extra money if you want a real commercial style range. In dealing with Thor service and support for another appliance I had of theirs in the past, they have not been competent at all. Just save yourself a headache and buy something that's not made by this company. In fact; Thor doesn't even make these things. They buy from large scale suppliers overseas and glue their logo on.

Avoid at all costs.

Good freezer, though I think the instructions need to be better... It seems that when the freezer is set to MAX, there is some kind of quick-freeze setting that is not mentioned in the manual. With my freezer, I set the temperature to MAX on the initial use, because it is hot out here in the desert, even in the middle of winter. The freezer refused to go below 10 degrees with about 4 gallons of water inside. In fact, it would go down to 10, then drift back up to 20, before going back to 10.

I moved the freezer, thinking it was not getting enough airflow, and it did the same thing, after testing for two days, I shut it off. The next day, I turned it back on, but only set it to medium. With a few hours, it was at 0 degrees, and by the next day it was below zero.

I think the MAX setting must runt the compressor constantly, then cycle the compressor off after a while to avoid overheating it, while the lower settings can turn the compressor on and off at will.

Again, this was not mentioned in the manual, but another brand of freezer I have has a similar setting, so I should have known. (Should be stated in the manual though.)

I did let the freezer stand for over 24 hours before using it to avoid problems from shipping, though the manual only recommends 2 hours. That seems insufficient, and I would recommend at least 24. Also, the manual states that "too much food" can cause the freezer to run inefficiently. Yes, if packed too tight to allow airflow, i think this is true, but the fuller a freezer is, the better it operates in my understanding. Later it warns against adding too much warm food at a time, which is a separate case.

In any case, the manual could use some serious improvement, but the freeze itself works great..

Most reviews are done early in the ownership lifetime of the appliance. Here‚Äôs a longer run view of the design flaws that exist in LG dishwashers.

I am replacing my high end LG dishwasher after less than two years of use. The dishwasher failed due to a cracked fitting on the water intake which failed during the night and caused about $10K in damage to a kitchen hardwood floor, and to drywall and carpeting in a finished basement. This was not the first problem with this dishwasher.

While the LG dishwasher never cleaned as well as the GE dishwasher that it replaced, over time it has become apparent that it has a number of fundamental design flaws. The drain path has several cavities where water and food can accumulate. As a result, the dishwasher began to smell after about a year of service. Food became trapped in the drain path and even though I used a pressure washer to try and clean out the sump and drain path, it was impossible to get it completely cleaned out and the smell persisted.

A second, more disastrous problem occurred this past week. The water intake valve failed completely and water out overnight. By the time the leak was discovered in the morning it had destroyed a kitchen hardwood floor which also into a finished basement destroying carpet and drywall in the process.

I wish that I had checked the reviews before buying this product. LG is ranked across the internet as the least reliable dishwasher on the market.

My dryer has about a 25 foot run but has 4 right angle bends along it‚Äôs path. Rule of thumb, adding 5 feet for every right angle bend, makes this equivalent to a 45 foot run! After a few years my wife was complaining clothes weren‚Äôt drying and she had to run them through 3 times to get them dry. Decided to clean the vent duct. It was clogged and packed with lint. How to clean out a vent duct like this is another story. Anyway, decided I needed to add a vent fan and bought this one. The dryer is in our mud room on the first floor with no space or good place to put this fan. Also, wanted this fan far enough away from living space so the noise it makes isn‚Äôt annoying. The dryer duct goes into our unfinished basement and then, through a crazy route out the back of the house. Found a good spot along the duct run to mount the fan on the underside of the first floor joists and luckily it was close enough to an existing electrical outlet that only a short extension cord was needed to plug it in. Now the question was how to turn it on and off without having to go down to the basement and plug or unplug the fan. The fan comes with a current sensor that probably works great but wiring it in my situation means running new wire through the wall from the mud room to the basement and a little knowledge of how to do it. The instructions that come with the current sensor are minimal but other posters have supplied helpful information on how to hook it up. Anyway my simple solution was to use an Alexa compatible plug. I named it ‚Äúdryer vent‚Äù. I plugged it into the outlet in the basement and plugged the fan into it. Now when we use the dryer we just say ‚ÄúAlexa, turn on dryer vent‚Äù and when the dryer is done say ‚ÄúAlexa, turn off dryer vent‚Äù. I also set up ‚Äúroutines‚Äù in the Alexa app for timing the fan to turn on and off with one command. Example: ‚Äú Alexa turn on dryer vent for 30 minutes‚Äù. I made a few different routines for different times ( 30 minutes, 40 minutes, one hour, etc.) Granted, using the sensor is seamless but the way I did is much simpler especially if you aren‚Äôt comfortable messing with electrical wiring.
As far as the fan itself goes, mine came with a dent in one of the round openings where the vent tubing connects. I was able to straighten it out using a pliers. Not perfect but not a problem. The length of the round openings where the vent duct connects could be a little longer to ensure a secure connection but it does work. The fan does make a far amount of noise and I wouldn‚Äôt recommend placing it an area where noise would be annoying. The fan itself does work very well and the drying ability of our dryer improved dramatically.

just received today and washed ONE load in a 5-gallon bucket & ONE in a 17-gallon tub!!
it is a MOST IMPRESSIVE clothes washer!!!!! i love it
the agitation is strong in both containers!! BUT GENTLE on the cloths- more like a front-load washer than a top-load!!

it is a little noisy- a little lower than a Vita-Mix Blender noise! so not too bad in my apartment with a neighbor next to my bathroom wall!! BUT if you have no neighbors next to your wall- it is NOT something that would bother you in the next room- if my neighbor complains i will just put it on the patio!

it also does splash a little water out so it needs to be in a bathtub or outside! not so much splash that it needs refilling but just enough to make a mess on the floor

this last year or two i have been using a plunger for agitation in the same containers- which works good but this is so much better- a couple of minutes at 1st- then let it soak and later come back to agitate 5 or 10 minutes more and the wash is done- then draw rinse water and agitate a few minutes-- i have a HIGH-SPEED-SPINNER which gets 95% of the water out so hanging 2 or 3 hours they will dry and ZERO DRIPPING!!

My very fine Kenmore 90 Series dryer quit running after almost 20 years, and after a few online searches, I knew it was the motor.  I considered just buying a dryer off of Craigslist, but decided that for the same price, or less, I could get my nice one running again.  I've read several reviews of this replacement motor...some say it's a cheap knock-off, some say it is the real deal.  I am here to tell you that this is definitely the real thing.  The box clearly states that it is a Whirlpool part, and the part number shown matches up exactly.  The wiring for the broken belt switch was changed, but it wasn't that hard to figure out, and instructions were included.  I was able to install the new motor using some youtube videos and my dryer is once again purring away.  You can buy this one with confidence!
